Subject: NVMe Storage Optimization for Sybase Temporary Filesystems
As part of the storage performance optimization on this server, we reviewed the current configuration of the two NVMe disks (nvme0n1 and nvme1n1) used for Sybase temporary and dump filesystems.
To improve both performance and resilience, we implemented a mirrored RAID1 configuration using LVM across the two NVMe devices. This setup ensures data redundancy while allowing both disks to participate efficiently in I/O operations.
Two logical volumes of 30 GB each were created within the volume group vg_tempdb:
/apps/sybase/dump/ESY3_FR_UAT_ASE
/apps/sybasetmp/ESY3_FR_UAT_ASE
Both filesystems are formatted with XFS and mounted with optimized parameters suitable for database workloads.
This architecture provides:
High I/O performance leveraging NVMe capabilities
Data protection through RAID1 mirroring
Flexibility for future storage expansion via LVM
The configuration has been verified and is ready for production use.
